I’ve been coming here since 2004 and am so grateful Bedouin Tent seems to be surviving the pandemic. I haven’t lived in the neighborhood for years but it’s always a special treat for us to stop by, from a casual lunch to a cozy birthday dinner. The same guys have been there for years, and the lifer waiters always greet us warmly even if we haven't stopped in for months. We are obsessed with the zaatar bread—everything on the menu is delicious but don't overlook that one. The food is always so fresh and it's a real comfort to know that this gem on Atlantic endures.

I’ve been going to Bedouin tent for well over 7 years and it’s quite the neighborhood staple. I’d like to provide recommendations on all the food and it might be expected since I’ve frequented over the years however, my go to is always the leg of lamb sandwich which has onions, tomatoes, a homemade mint mayo in pita - I typically get it with spicy sauce as well as the basbousa for dessert. It just hits the spot each time so no reason to explore the rest of the menu. I’ve had the pitza on occasion which is a middle eastern version of pizza. Service is always superb.

Fantastic Middle Eastern restaurant serving delicious regional dishes. All the food is made fresh and in house, including the pita which one can observe at the front of the restaurant. The dining room is located in the back, and is adorned with fabrics and light fixtures transporting one outside of Brooklyn. Did I also mention the food is delicious?!

This is more of a take out place than dine in. They are best known for Pitzas and pita wraps, and they just give more food for the platters. I will say that theres not a lot of variety, but what they serve, they do well.  It took a while for seating (20 mins) but that was also because the outside wasnt open as yet- they have a backyard garden. Its fun to stand in front and watch the pita being made though. Also, they mostly deal in cash.  I tried the merguez sausage wrap and the fava beans for the side, my friend G got the falafels. All the food was very solid meditteranean but unfortunately not really outstanding in terms of taste. I will say that it was all very fresh and well prepared and the servers were good with noting my friends allergies and making sure that the kitchen was prepared to serve her. The food came really quickly to the table too.  The place has a fun cool vibe to it, I loved the orange tapestry work. I would come here for a quick bite or to grab lunch.

I’m giving three stars because I enjoyed the lentil soup, but this place isn’t all that. If you want real middle eastern food in the area go to the Yemen Cafe a couple blocks away.

There are plenty of other options too - whether vegetarian or meat meal. Very friendly server and kitchen staff too. Low prices.

This is a story being circulated in order to boycott your store and you may want to change your policy as social networking is very influential!! "So I go to BEDOUIN TENT restaurant last night with my fiancée, Tiffy Smile. We get the check and I notice it is a smidge higher than I expected. I say to myself out loud, oh they added the tip already. No biggie. The people to my immediate right and left had coincidentally asked for their checks at the same time. They overheard me and re-checked their bills. No tip added. I immediately called over the manager and asked him why the table on the right had not been charged a tip. He explained to me that it was because they were regulars and only new people were charged gratuity. This of course made me ask the table on the left if they were regulars. Needless to say, it was their first time there. The manager tried to make another lame excuse and I could not help but notice that there was only one difference between me and the people around Tiffany and I and it wasn't the color of our hair. As you can imagine, I was furious. Racism sucks. ‪#‎BoycottBedouinTent‬"
